WEBVTT

1
00:00:28.300 --> 00:00:31.860
Asymmetric collapse, asymmetric collapse with straight-ahead flight.

2
00:00:31.860 --> 00:00:39.100
With asymmetric collapse, like with various other collapses, it's the case that, when

3
00:00:39.100 --> 00:00:44.860
we collapse one side, it brakes the wing — so remember,

4
00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:50.660
pulling ears, everything that collapses brakes; in this case it brakes the right side considerably,

5
00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:54.380
and a movement to the right would actually result.

6
00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:58.780
So the wing would happily build up dynamics to the right — we don't want that.

7
00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:24.220
We want, we want with that collapse to (unclear)

8
00:01:24.220 --> 00:01:25.220
of which side.

9
00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:32.220
And then we want to slow that down with the counter-brake. Why with the counter-brake — I'll explain right away.

10
00:01:32.220 --> 00:01:39.220
In theory, it's like this — you also have to tick this off, if the question comes up in flight practice.

11
00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:49.220
To stabilise the asymmetric collapse, you additionally have to put body weight onto this open side and brake a bit less with it.

12
00:01:49.220 --> 00:01:55.220
But in practice it's like this: with a 50% collapse maybe that still works.

13
00:01:55.220 --> 00:02:02.220
With 60–70% — which really is more of the problem for us — that doesn't work any more.

14
00:02:02.220 --> 00:02:08.220
That means, you have so much load gone from the right riser. You can't manage to lean over to the left side at all.

15
00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:15.220
And it's not even productive. If we let the weight fall onto the collapsed side,

16
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:21.220
then the riser is first loaded again on that side.

17
00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:26.220
That means we help the wing much sooner to re-open.

18
00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:31.220
So, letting the weight fall — you can also remember this for flying.

19
00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:38.220
Letting body weight fall is always good — you always load exactly the side that needs to be loaded right then.

20
00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:40.220
That's why we do it that way too.

21
00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:43.220
Good, how can we fly the whole thing?

22
00:02:43.220 --> 00:02:48.220
Correct is of course that we try to collapse this 40–50% surface.

23
00:02:48.220 --> 00:03:02.220
And we manage that by first of all, on the collapse side, fixing the brake to the press-stud.

24
00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:05.220
Or magnet, like here — it doesn't matter.

25
00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:09.220
Or you just let it go, but don't keep it in your hand.

26
00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:17.220
Because if we now pull the A-risers and have the brake in the hand, the brake maybe gets messed up,

27
00:03:17.220 --> 00:03:22.220
then it doesn't really know what it should do — should it collapse, or should it re-open.

28
00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:28.220
So brake away, best to fix it, then it makes the least chaos.

29
00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:33.220
The other brake stays unwrapped, but right up at the bridle in the hand.

30
00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:37.220
There, if you want, you can brace yourself a bit on the riser,

31
00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:41.220
so the hand doesn't fly off somewhere into nothing.

32
00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:43.220
So lightly braced on the riser.

33
00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:48.380
Never grip the riser, but always only brace on it.

34
00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:51.380
Good, then come maybe also a bit forward.

35
00:03:51.380 --> 00:03:56.380
It's important that you absolutely come over the line locks, all the A-lines.

36
00:03:56.380 --> 00:03:59.380
That means, also the high-attachment aids.

37
00:03:59.380 --> 00:04:01.380
You have to take them along too.

38
00:04:01.380 --> 00:04:06.380
So all the A-lines that you have, take along — grab above the line locks like this:

39
00:04:06.380 --> 00:04:11.380
little fingers up, and index finger and thumb wrap around the line lock,

40
00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:13.380
so above the line lock.

41
00:04:13.380 --> 00:04:18.380
And then you can pull — at the beginning pull a bit slowly,

42
00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:22.380
then fix the A-lines, because otherwise it opens straight back up on you.

43
00:04:23.380 --> 00:04:28.670
Pull, and where you have it just right, you can hold yourself on the main riser.

44
00:04:28.670 --> 00:04:32.670
And now carefully work with the left brake.

45
00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:38.050
All by feel, search for straight flight, search for straight-ahead flight.

46
00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:40.050
And then with the, straight-ahead flight,

47
00:04:40.050 --> 00:04:43.050
the 13,000, with the fingers.

48
00:04:43.050 --> 00:04:46.050
It's not necessarily the case

49
00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:48.050
that you pull the brake and can then keep it there,

50
00:04:48.050 --> 00:04:50.050
but you may have to work a bit.

51
00:04:50.050 --> 00:04:53.050
That's why searching for this flight is so important,

52
00:04:53.050 --> 00:04:55.050
look at a fixed point in the terrain to the wing,

53
00:04:55.050 --> 00:04:57.050
look forward.

54
00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.050
Aha, now I'm flying straight ahead, wonderful.

55
00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:02.050
Now comes the command from me, release the collapse.

56
00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:06.050
Okay, then the right hand — as the collapsed side — simply goes up.

57
00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:09.050
The left hand keeps searching for straight-ahead flight.

58
00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:11.080
Until the collapse is out.

59
00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:14.080
And then the counter-brake can simply be released up.

60
00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:18.720
Under no circumstances simply let everything go,

61
00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:22.720
because if the collapse is in, then we turn off to the right onto the collapsed side.

62
00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:23.720
We don't want that.

63
00:05:23.720 --> 00:05:27.720
So that's why, just stabilise the opposite side

64
00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:28.720
until the collapse is out.

65
00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:30.720
If it doesn't come out on its own,

66
00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:34.720
then we grab the brake, take the brake and pump once.

67
00:05:34.720 --> 00:05:35.720
Snap!

68
00:05:35.720 --> 00:05:36.720
Pay!

69
00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:37.720
Still straight-ahead flight.

70
00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:38.720
How to stabilise?

71
00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:39.720
Look — where's it going?

72
00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:40.720
All right.

73
00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:42.720
Wing is still not open.

74
00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:43.720
21, 22, 22.

75
00:05:43.720 --> 00:05:45.720
Damn, I'll give it one more, right?

76
00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:46.720
Then it's open.

77
00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:49.720
And if I had to pump again,

78
00:05:49.720 --> 00:05:51.720
but always at about two, three seconds apart.

79
00:05:51.720 --> 00:05:53.720
And if that's the case,

80
00:05:53.720 --> 00:05:54.720
it's not the case here in the courtyard.

81
00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:56.720
Then we can wait again with both hands.

82
00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:00.960
Or, with the ears hand all the way up.

83
00:06:00.960 --> 00:06:01.960
Now!

84
00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:06.120
Why work so carefully with the counter-brake?

85
00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:09.120
We have a very, very short steering travel.

86
00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:12.120
We have 50% surface that we have collapsed.

87
00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:16.720
That means we still only have 50% surface that's flying.

88
00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:19.720
Wing loading rises enormously.

89
00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:22.720
And with wing loading the stall point also rises.

90
00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:25.720
That means, we've reached the stall point much sooner.

91
00:06:25.720 --> 00:06:28.720
So steering travel has become noticeably shorter.

92
00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:31.720
And the pressure in the wing.

93
00:06:31.720 --> 00:06:35.720
So, just on the side, on the brake — it's enormously high.

94
00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:38.720
That means, brake pressure has also become higher.

95
00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:41.720
So you really have to fly sensitively,

96
00:06:41.720 --> 00:06:44.720
very sensitively searching for straight-ahead flight.

97
00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:47.720
And the whole thing of course, train it a couple of times.

98
00:06:47.720 --> 00:06:49.720
Once left, once right,

99
00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:51.720
so we don't get too set in our ways.

100
00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:54.000
Okay.

101
00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:59.000
If we've now gotten too little surface in for the asymmetric collapse,

102
00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
then we can go at it again.

103
00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So let go, I'll say, let go again,

104
00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:05.000
go at it again.

105
00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Then we have to try to pull a bit more aggressively.

106
00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
We have to always come to 50%.

107
00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
We're also allowed in training to fly 60%.

108
00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.000
Or 70% goes, depending, when we have good altitude.

109
00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
But the important thing is, when we really have too little.

110
00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And it's like, 40%, then I say to you,

111
00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:25.000
a bit more aggressively.

112
00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
So then we can go at it.

113
00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:29.160
Pull a bit more aggressively.

114
00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:31.160
Maybe then pull a bit deeper too.

115
00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:35.160
And the wing also lays itself much better backwards from the collapse.

116
00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:39.160
And then again on exactly the same — carefully counter.

117
00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:42.160
Just so far that it flies straight ahead

118
00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:46.160
and hold the straight-ahead, until the command-giver lets the collapse out.

119
00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:49.160
And then again, nothing first — release the collapse,

120
00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:54.530
and then the brake, when the wing is open.

121
00:07:54.530 --> 00:07:56.530
Simply that's it for the collapse.

122
00:07:56.530 --> 00:07:58.530
Once right, once left — always remember.

123
00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.530
On the collapse side, fix the brake beforehand.

124
00:08:01.530 --> 00:08:02.530
Because if you don't,

125
00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:05.530
and I think, when pulled down, you'll see.

126
00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:07.530
The wing won't collapse very well.

127
00:08:07.530 --> 00:08:11.530
There it really needs the brake free,

128
00:08:11.530 --> 00:08:13.530
so not even kept in the hand.

129
00:08:13.530 --> 00:08:15.690
Good, okay.
